  	    "description": "You think your job sucks? Trade with Robert Gibbs. His boss is \u0022methodical.\u0022 His workplace is hostile. His job is Sisyphean. And, everyone is blaming him for a communication problem that may hand Washington to the opposition. Inside the woeful world of the White House press secretary",
  	    "articleBody": "FacebookPinterest\u000A\u000A If to some the beltway resembles a high school for bright but hopelessly status-fixated souls, then the James S. Brady Press Briefing Room is its detention hall, where the caste system is both starkly defined and trumped by a prevailing atmosphere of shared misery. The basement-level room—fittingly named after the victim of a madman—is, despite a makeover three years ago, cramped, colorless, and harshly illuminated. Its forty-nine seats remain empty most weekdays until sometime after noon, when a stern female voice announces over the intercom, \u0022This is a two-minute warning for the start of the press briefing. Two minutes...\u0022\u000A\u000AThe reporters shuffle in and take their assigned seats. Journalists from little-known organizations such as Salem Radio, the Washington Examiner, and the Christian Broadcasting Network are relegated to the two back rows. A muddle of the emergent (Politico) and the endangered (Newsweek) inhabits the middle three. The stalwarts of print and radio sit in the second. And in the front, we find (along with AP and Reuters) the five TV-network correspondents—your Chip Reids (CBS), your Chuck Todds (NBC), your Ed Henrys (CNN)—who, in the way of cool kids everywhere, tend to make their entrance well after the two minutes have elapsed. Everyone gazes at the door just to the left of the podium as if willing it to swing open. Eventually it does. From an upstairs office, a few steps away from the one occupied by President Barack Obama, press secretary Robert Gibbs descends for his near-daily encounter with the White House press corps.\u000A\u000AOn this afternoon—Friday the thirteenth of August—Gibbs is accompanied by Homeland Security secretary Janet Napolitano to tout a rare bipartisan victory for the White House: a bill that will secure the Mexican-American border with up to 1,200 National Guardsmen and two unmanned aircraft. Half of the questions Napolitano fields relate to the content of the bill. The other half are about process—the choreography of modern politics: \u0022getting Republicans to the table,\u0022 the \u0022timetable for the next step,\u0022 Congress saying that \u0022leadership in the White House is needed.\u0022 Gibbs hates these kinds of questions, which seem to imply that the ends are less important than the means and the motives. But he maintains his placid Buddha-Bubba countenance throughout Napolitano\u0027s expert retorts. Forty minutes later, the secretary steps back, and it is Gibbs\u0027s turn behind the podium.\u000A\u000AThe reporters first rattle off a few questions about the progress of the oil-spill cleanup. Then about the economic recovery, then: \u0022On the president\u0027s trip [to the Gulf Coast] this weekend...any plans to get in the water?\u0022\u000A\u000AGibbs smirks. \u0022I doubt that will go out specifically on the guidance\u0022—the president\u0027s daily schedule—\u0022but stay tuned.\u0022\u000A\u000AThey persist, from each row. \u0022Will we get in the water, and will there be pictures?\u0022 \u0022Are the waters clean enough to get into?\u0022 \u0022Would that say something, if he takes a walk down the beach but doesn\u0027t put his feet in the water?\u0022\u000A\u000A\u0022Guys,\u0022 Gibbs sighs, clearly exasperated, \u0022why don\u0027t we all worry about what happens on Saturday.\u0022\u000A\u000AA couple of hours after the briefing, the press secretary is in his office, sitting behind a semicircular desk that is itself a disaster site: teetering jumbles of paper, a spent tea bag, randomly affid Post-it scribbles from his 7-year-old son, a computer screen endlessly hiccuping with newly received e-mails, and a small TV split four ways to reveal four little heads, none of whom seem to be talking about Napolitano\u0027s briefing. Gibbs is probably tired, but it\u0027s hard to say for sure. His 39-year-old face is more like a shield, with an immense forehead and tiny eyes that scarcely radiate. The smile, affable and empty, could be that of a small-town gas-station attendant or a hired assassin.\u000A\u000AGibbs is about to surf the Internet to read what, if anything, has been written about the border bill. \u0022Few issues have been covered with as much emotion as immigration has over the past two months,\u0022 he says. \u0022It\u0027ll be interesting to see if something on the affirmative side of the ledger can garner any attention.\u0022 Still, he\u0027s clearly chapped about all of the \u0022what does this mean politically\u0022 questions. \u0022Lord knows, we have proved fairly adroitly over the previous eighteen months that the decisions we make are not predicated on the polls,\u0022 he says. \u0022Because if they were, we\u0027d have new want ads for pollsters, right?\u0022 And that probing line of inquiry about whether the president will brave the tainted Gulf waters strikes him as fairly \u0022pointless\u0022—though as one of the correspondents had said to me right after the briefing, \u0022Why does he have to be testy about it? If he just gave a straightforward answer, that would\u0027ve been the end of it.\u0022\u000A\u000AIn any event, none of this really matters. Despite Gibbs\u0027s efforts, the big news of the day won\u0027t be the successful passage of the border-security bill. Nor will it be whether Obama will go swimming tomorrow. That evening, at a White House gathering of Muslims, the president will declare that he supports the right of the Cordoba House planners to build an Islamic center just two blocks northeast of Ground Zero—a story to swamp all stories. Later, I asked White House communications director Dan Pfeiffer why Obama decided to step all over Napolitano\u0027s message. Pfeiffer patiently explained that \u0022there are an exponential number of news cycles per day,\u0022 that \u0022there\u0027s an infinite amount of time between the briefing and what he said that night,\u0022 and that the mosque matter \u0022is something the president wanted to weigh in on, and [the Muslim event] had been on the calendar for months.\u0022\u000A\u000ASo even as Gibbs sat at his desk ruminating over whether the media was willing to cover something \u0022on the affirmative side of the ledger,\u0022 he knew it was a long shot. No matter how many border briefings he held that day, only one message would dominate the next several news cycles. And like so many stories about the White House lately, it was not an altogether affirmative one.\u000A\u000A···\u000A\u000A President Obama, the finest orator-politician since Ronald Reagan, has a communications problem. In less than two years in office, the man who talked himself out of obscurity and into the White House has managed to alienate both Wall Street and Main Street. Health care reform, initially hailed as a blockbuster legislative achievement, is now universally considered a political liability. Even his persona, once so crisp and inspiring, now comes off as murky, professorial, and insular—a foil for the fusillade of rage being broadcast daily from the far right.\u000A\u000AIndeed, six years after convincing millions of rapt convention-watchers that \u0022my story is part of the larger American story,\u0022 Obama is seen by many as playing for some team other than America\u0027s. It may be true that, as Robert Gibbs told me, \u0022it\u0027s hard to message 9.5 percent unemployment,\u0022 but here\u0027s another verity: When an activist president is seemingly credited for nothing and blamed for everything, he\u0027s doing a lousy job of selling himself.\u000A\u000APanic-stricken Democrats, fearful of losing both the House and the Senate in this month\u0027s elections, can console themselves with a perspective check. \u0022Every president has a communications problem,\u0022 says former Clinton senior adviser Joel Johnson, who points out that at this point in their respective presidencies, Obama\u0027s approval rating of 44 eclipses those of Clinton and Reagan. Adds former Clinton press secretary Joe Lockhart, \u0022Honestly, the guy could walk on water and there\u0027d be exposés on \u0027What\u0027s in the water?\u0027 I think they\u0027ve taken the proper view, which is that they\u0027re going to get judged once, and that\u0027s in November 2012.\u0022\u000A\u000AThen again, do they have any other choice? The selling of a president—any president—has become an increasingly Sisyphean undertaking since the days when Michael Deaver achieved genius status simply for making Reagan camera-ready. Dan Pfeiffer points out what\u0027s obvious to anyone who watches a few minutes of cable news, that political communications today are a frantic, Hieronymus Bosch–like dystopia: \u0022The basic philosophy is, the beast is either feeding on you or feeding on someone else. The media is more combative an enterprise than ever before—combative with the White House, newspapers literally fighting for their economic lives every day. You have outlets of ideological agendas in the briefing room on both sides who ask questions that fuel the debate. Every reporter sitting in that room, whether they admit it or not, wants to ask something that\u0027ll lead the Huffington Post. So it\u0027s incredibly provocative.\u0022\u000A\u000AInto this breach wades Robert Lane Gibbs, the person best suited to sell Barack Obama to the rest of us. That\u0027s according to Gibbs himself, \u0022because of my knowledge of how he thinks and how he reacts.\u0022 Gibbs occupies the West Wing\u0027s innermost circle, which at press time included chief of staff Rahm Emanuel and senior advisers David Alrod and Valerie Jarrett. Gibbs knows Washington better than Jarrett and Alrod do, and he knows Obama better than Emanuel does. The Auburn, Alabama, native with the sorghum drawl also knows Middle America better than all of them. According to former communications director Anita Dunn, Obama relies on Gibbs to \u0022bring a blue-collar political perspective to issues.\u0022 Consequently, he has become the White House\u0027s primary stopgap for one of Obama\u0027s biggest shortcomings: his populist deficit. As Obama\u0027s tendency is to deliberate, then triangulate, then orate, then stay above the fray as his decisions slowly play out, it falls on Gibbs and, occasionally, Vice President Joe Biden­ to fight their boss\u0027s battles and to project evidence that our president gives a damn about us and knows what he\u0027s doing.\u000A\u000AWhen I asked Gibbs if it was true that no press secretary in recent memory has enjoyed the kind of interaction he has with the president, I figured that he would demur modestly. Instead, he replied, \u0022I don\u0027t think I disagree.\u0022 The pair\u0027s bond, rooted in Realpolitik and swaddled in masculine affect—\u0022Oh, my God, on the guy level it\u0027s unbelievable, I mean it\u0027s real guy stuff,\u0022 says one female associate—is especially manifest inside the White House, where Gibbs\u0027s portfolio extends far beyond the Brady briefing room.\u000A\u000AIt was Gibbs, for example, who was sitting in the press office one Monday evening in June when he remembers calling Obama to tell him, \u0022Hey, I\u0027ve got this article from Rolling Stone about General McChrystal that I think you need to see. Can you meet me at the elevator in the Residence?\u0022\u000A\u000A\u0022Yeah, I heard about this,\u0022 replied the president, who had been tipped off about the story by Vice President Biden. \u0022How bad is it?\u0022\u000A\u000A\u0022You\u0027re going to want to read it,\u0022 he said.\u000A\u000AThe two men met at the Residence, and Gibbs handed him the article. Obama thumbed through it while the press secretary rattled off its highlights. \u0022Let\u0027s go back to the Oval Office,\u0022 the president said, then asked Gibbs to summon a few other advisers. Together, they conferenced in the Oval to discuss the options. Secretary of Defense Robert Gates initially recommended that the general be reprimanded. Gibbs and others argued that McChrystal had undermined the commander in chief and therefore must go. Obama sided with Gibbs\u0027s faction.\u000A\u000ANo sooner had Obama publicly beheaded McChrystal that Wednesday than a fresh catastrophe crossed Gibbs\u0027s desk: An undersea robotic vehicle in the Gulf had dislodged the containment cap on the BP well. Until the lid was reattached eleven hours later, a new torrent of oil spilled into the sea. Gibbs went back into the Oval to give Obama the news.\u000A\u000AThe president stared at Gibbs, stunned. \u0022Well, why did it do that?\u0022 he demanded.\u000A\u000A\u0022Sir, we\u0027re trying to find that out.\u0022\u000A\u000A\u0022Gibbs,\u0022 Obama said, \u0022your job the rest of the day is to make sure that one of those vehicles doesn\u0027t do that again.\u0022\u000A\u000A···\u000A\u000A Gibbs was present at the creation, the spring of 2004, when Barack Obama was a senatorial aspirant with a campaign staff of nine and a memoir that maybe nine people had read. Thirty-three at the time, Gibbs possessed exactly the middle-American sensibility Obama, with his singular Hawaii-to-Indonesia upbringing, lacked. The son of two librarians, Gibbs was a soccer jock who had attended only public schools, graduated from North Carolina State, and labored for a series of congressmen and senators. He was a loyalist, having quit John Kerry\u0027s presidential campaign in November 2003 after Kerry fired Gibbs\u0027s boss and friend Jim Jordan. A few years later, Jordan returned the favor, suggesting that Alrod—who was then running Obama\u0027s Senate campaign—hire Gibbs as the team\u0027s communications director.\u000A\u000ADuring the summer of 2004, Gibbs accompanied Obama to diners and town halls throughout Illinois. Together they would hash out what lines worked and which ones didn\u0027t. Particularly downstate—which, as Gibbs points out, \u0022is closer to Little Rock than it is to Chicago\u0022—the southerner\u0027s working-class antenna was a useful thing to have around. \u0022Look, I want you to be able to tell me whatever you need to tell me,\u0022 Gibbs remembers the senator-elect saying right after the election.\u000A\u000AIn the episodic years that followed, Obama and Gibbs spent countless hours on the road together, and along the way the latter became a reliable barometer of the former\u0027s moods and a counterbalance to his disposition. As the Obama presidential campaign\u0027s traveling press secretary—or \u0022point of the spear,\u0022 as he aptly puts it—Gibbs provided brute force to Obama\u0027s gauzy \u0022change\u0022 theme. In one postdebate exchange, for example, Gibbs challenged Fox host Sean Hannity\u0027s claim that Obama was guilty by his association with William Ayers—pointing out that Hannity had featured Andy Martin, an influential hatemonger, on a special edition of his show. \u0022Are you anti-Semitic?\u0022 Gibbs pressed his inquisitor. The showdown got a lot of YouTube attention, but it wasn\u0027t Gibbs\u0027s only dustup that election. According to one of the veteran correspondents of the campaign, Gibbs seemed to \u0022wake up every morning relishing ripping apart his opponents.\u0022\u000A\u000AGibbs was already destined to become (along with Alrod, Jarrett, and Pete Rouse) a White House senior adviser. The question was whether he would also serve as the Obama administration\u0027s press secretary. Few besides Gibbs seemed to think that it was such a hot idea. According to multiple sources, a number of his colleagues from the campaign attempted to dissuade the fiery southerner. At least three former White House press secretaries—Lockhart, Mike McCurry, and George Stephanopoulos, all from the Clinton administration—separately warned him that the two positions were too demanding for one person. \u0022I did both jobs at the same time,\u0022 Stephanopoulos told him, \u0022and ended up not doing very well at either of them.\u0022 Additionally, Joel Johnson remembers cautioning Gibbs that \u0022where as senior adviser you\u0027re the advocate to the president, as press secretary you have a dual advocacy role.\u0022 To several in Obama World, the notion of Robert Gibbs as \u0022press advocate\u0022 was laughable—and Obama himself, when he first offered the job to Gibbs, instructed his new press secretary not to play the role of the bad cop.\u000A\u000ABut by most objective standards, Gibbs has proved himself more than worthy of the podium. Each morning he spends about three hours poring over the media reports and attending policy briefings. As one veteran White House correspondent told me, \u0022His deputies don\u0027t have to spend the whole afternoon cleaning up after him the way Tony Snow\u0027s deputies did.\u0022 And unlike his predecessors, who stuck largely to the script because Bush preferred to break news himself, Gibbs can be quite expansive. \u0022Everyone says Robert\u0027s a completely different press secretary,\u0022 says Pfeiffer. \u0022But it\u0027s a completely different job. Siloing doesn\u0027t work anymore, because everything has a million implications. Congressional, political, press—it all feeds on each other. So Gibbs is expected to know more than the average press secretary.\u0022\u000A\u000AHis abilities notwithstanding, Gibbs seems especially gifted at offending fellow Democrats. One veteran Democratic communications strategist finds Gibbs\u0027s conduct \u0022snarky\u0022 and \u0022arrogant,\u0022 pointing to an incident last February when Gibbs gratuitously mocked Sarah Palin by showing up to a briefing with handwriting on his left palm. (\u0022I wrote down \u0027hope\u0027 and \u0027change\u0027 just in case I forgot.\u0022) Perhaps more troubling to the left was Gibbs\u0027s remark in July that Republicans might very well take back the House. This may have seemed like a case of stating the obvious. But Speaker Nancy Pelosi called the comment \u0022unfortunate,\u0022 and Gibbs refused to walk it back.\u000A\u000AIn general, however, the left\u0027s criticisms of Gibbs tend to fall into two categories. The first is that the press secretary can be overly protective of the president. While several current and former White House officials told me that Gibbs often brings uncomfortable truths into the Oval Office—as economic adviser Larry Summers recently told a reporter, \u0022The only person from the campaign who\u0027ll speak bluntly to the president is Gibbs\u0022—his impulse nonetheless is to insulate Obama from political fallout. A prime example occurred this summer when the White House backed the USDA\u0027s decision to fire Shirley Sherrod after a Web video showed the federal employee giving a seemingly racist speech. Initially, Gibbs failed to investigate the origins of the clip. Instead, while Sherrod was telling reporters that the snippet grossly misrepresented her overall message, Gibbs was on the phone encouraging USDA chief Tom Vilsack to issue a statement emphasizing that the decision to fire her was solely his. It was Gibbs\u0027s impulse to insulate Obama that ultimately backfired: An administration employee with a glowing civil rights backstory had been smeared by right-wing scalp-hunter Andrew Breitbart and the White House appeared to sacrifice one of their own. According to an individual who is close to both the president and his senior team, \u0022The problem is that in attempting to cauterize the wound, you stab yourself deeply.\u0022 (The same source says the racial subtext of Sherrod\u0027s firing may also have contributed to Gibbs\u0027s squeamishness: \u0022Gibbs sees himself as the voice of the average guy. And so he tends to be aggressive in not having that sort of conversation [about race].\u0022)\u000A\u000AGibbs\u0027s zealous engagement with foes—both real and imagined—leads to the second major criticism of the press secretary: that he too often directs his ire at progressives instead of at the administration\u0027s many opponents on the right. A memorable instance occurred on August 10, when Gibbs was out sick and his deputy, Bill Burton, replaced him in the briefing room. The day\u0027s major talking point was supposed to be the bill Obama would sign a few hours later that would save 160,000 teachers\u0027 jobs. Instead, most of the questions focused on sarcastic comments Gibbs had made the previous day to Sam Youngman of The Hill concerning liberal pundits who drive ratings by criticizing the president. Gibbs dubbed the talking heads the \u0022professional left,\u0022 adding that \u0022they ought to be drug tested\u0022 and \u0022they wouldn\u0027t be satisfied if Dennis Kucinich was president.\u0022\u000A\u000AUnsurprisingly, Gibbs has a ready explanation for what some see as his heightened states of protectiveness toward his boss and his aggressiveness toward his boss\u0027s critics. \u0022I think that the role of press secretary has forever changed,\u0022 he says. \u0022Those that are opposed to the president are more vocal and more organized and more prevalent than against any administration at any point in any time in our history.\u0022 And because attacks by a Sarah Palin, Rick Santelli, or liberal pundits occur almost daily and can immediately engulf the blogosphere, Gibbs says, he feels compelled to counterattack, swiftly and forcefully so that Obama himself—known for his cool above-it-allness—doesn\u0027t get caught in the crossfire. \u0022I\u0027m sure that there are people that say, \u0027Oh, gosh, the White House press secretary shouldn\u0027t do that,\u0027\u0022 he says. \u0022But at the same time, if the White House press secretary doesn\u0027t do it, who does—and gets on the news?\u0022\u000A\u000AOf course, to many on the left—including former president Bill Clinton—the Obama White House picks too few battles with the right, evincing a dismaying passivity to the rest. Gibbs has a far different view of things—which is that most of these provocations are utterly baseless, unworthy of anyone\u0027s attention...except that the media gives them undue airtime. Which leads us to one other rap on Obama\u0027s press secretary: Apparently Gibbs can\u0027t stand the press.\u000A\u000A···\u000A\u000AThe day after his inauguration, Barack Obama summoned his entire communications team to the Oval Office. Though the gathering was intended as a photo op, the president had something to tell them, according to one who was present—namely, that he wanted his administration to have a good relationship with the media. This was a somewhat surprising statement, given that Obama—unlike, say, John McCain—had never devoted much of his time to hanging out with reporters. \u0022My theory of Obama,\u0022 says one White House correspondent, \u0022is that he looks at the press and says, \u0027You people are reasonably smart, reasonably well educated—why aren\u0027t you doing something good with your life like I am?\u0027\u0022 According to David Mendell\u0027s seminal biography, Obama: From Promise to Power, during his 2006 trip to Kenya the senator at one point found himself surrounded by the traveling press and called out for Gibbs, saying, \u0022Where is the animal trainer? Where is the whip and chair?\u0022 Mendell reported that Obama\u0027s remark \u0022did not go over well with several reporters.\u0022\u000A\u000ARelations, in any event, are not good. Obama incessantly refers to \u0022the cable chatter\u0022 with palpable disdain, and he frequently grumbles to his aides about the media\u0027s coverage of his presidency. His press conferences are fewer than Clinton\u0027s (though more than Bush\u0027s) at the same stage of their presidencies—and, says Clinton\u0027s former press secretary Mike McCurry, \u0022I feel sometimes when I watch Obama do these that he looks like he\u0027d rather be having a root canal.\u0022 Obama does reserve a certain respect for opinion writers such as Tom Friedman and David Brooks of The New York Times, Jerry Seib of The Wall Street Journal, E. J. Dionne of The Washington Post, and Joe Klein of Time. \u0022My impression is that he reads a lot of columnists,\u0022 says Brooks, \u0022and therefore he sort of cares about what they say.\u0022\u000A\u000AThe press corps itself is another matter. \u0022When people ask me what it\u0027s like to cover the Obama White House after covering the Bush White House,\u0022 one correspondent told me, \u0022I say that there is no difference. The level of control is great or greater. The access to officials is maybe greater, but the information it produces is less.\u0022 Gibbs\u0027s press shop readily refutes such sentiments. They point out that at various junctures of his still-young presidency, Obama has been accused of overexposure. Besides the press, says McCurry, \u0022no one else in the country thinks we probably haven\u0027t seen enough of Barack Obama.\u0022 The White House\u0027s hostility toward the press corps extends far beyond Obama and Gibbs. Alrod calls the daily briefing \u0022part of the theater of the absurd that is the media frenzy of Washington.\u0022 While another official said of the media, \u0022They feel like [Gibbs] doesn\u0027t give them access to the president. And in many ways he doesn\u0027t. In many ways they don\u0027t deserve it.\u0022 But make no mistake: Gibbs\u0027s operation is Ground Zero for reporter loathing. It\u0027s where, according to a source close to the administration, certain White House correspondents are sometimes said to be referred to as \u0022terrorists.\u0022\u000A\u000AGibbs\u0027s casual contempt for journalists seems to be one of those unpleasant facts of life the White House media have come to expect. In Prague earlier this year, Gibbs told the traveling press to meet him for a goodwill dinner, then never showed up—and never bothered to respond to their where-are-you messages. The reporters were annoyed but not terribly surprised, as Gibbs is notoriously unresponsive. The press corps has become so accustomed to this behavior that they barely seemed to notice when the press secretary finished off a recent briefing by saying with a straight face, \u0022I\u0027ll do one more, and then I\u0027ll go back to work.\u0022\u000A\u000AIt would be unfair to paint Gibbs as callous. His subordinates seem to love him, and even those who regard him as a bully tell stories of him offering to show a journalist\u0027s relative around the White House or extending sympathies when personal misfortune has befallen a reporter. He does not seem to take the bruising give-and-take personally. If anything, says Dan Pfeiffer, Gibbs recognizes that \u0022a lot of the forces that make his job harder than previous press secretaries\u0027 make reporters\u0027 jobs harder.\u0022\u000A\u000AIf Gibbs possesses such empathy, he does not use it to the White House\u0027s advantage. Says a prominent Democratic communications strategist who is critical of Gibbs, \u0022Part of your job as press secretary is to defuse rather than aggravate tensions with the press.\u0022 Adds Mike McCurry, who counts himself as a Gibbs fan, \u0022You can try to circumvent them and say they\u0027re not as important as they used to be, but having those folks who cover you day in, day out, saying what you\u0027re about, still does matter. I still fall on the side that says amicable is better.\u0022\u000A\u000AIn his office, I ask Gibbs if the administration\u0027s view of the press has changed at all over the past year. He starts out hesitantly. \u0022No. I mean—\u0022\u000A\u000AOh, come on, I say.\u000A\u000A\u0022Look, I will say this. We still joke that if we watched cable for the hour before he made his decision to run for president, we\u0027d still be sitting in the Senate. You know, I don\u0027t doubt that [the president] has day-to-day frustrations—like when somebody says, \u0027We don\u0027t know what\u0027s in the health care bill. Didn\u0027t the president do a poor job of explaining what\u0027s in it?\u0027... I mean, Pew did that study of news coverage around health care, and I think 10 percent of it was on the legislation and 40 percent was on tactics and strategy and process. And then, you know, the day after the bill was signed, you walk into the briefing room and they say, \u0027How come nobody knows what\u0027s in it?\u0027 Or they\u0027ll say, \u0027What are the politics of nobody knowing what\u0027s in this bill?\u0027\u0022\u000A\u000AGibbs\u0027s characterization of the Pew Research Center\u0027s findings is accurate; of the press\u0027s questions following the bill signing, not accurate. Still, statements like these illustrate a seething exasperation that is mutually felt—and which reached a boiling point in the aftermath of the BP oil spill.\u000A\u000AGibbs and others in the press shop are understandably annoyed by the suggestion by some in the press that the spill was \u0022Obama\u0027s Katrina.\u0022 True to the president\u0027s deliberative style, the White House was slow to assume ownership of the response to the disaster. But the emblematic feature of Katrina—that the media were broadcasting the fiasco days before President Bush seemed aware of it—does not apply to this case. As Gibbs correctly points out, the press initially flocked to a single issue: the politics of oil exploration. \u0022Up until the point where I had a big briefing [on April 29, nine days after the oil-rig explosion],\u0022 he says, \u0022all of the questions I got were about the politics of drilling for oil.\u0022\u000A\u000AHad the press focused instead on the real issue—the efforts to plug the well—Gibbs says he would have been able to better deliver vital information. According to several administration officials, a week after the Deepwater Horizon explosion, Gibbs stepped into the BP communications void—not simply as a mouthpiece of talking points but as a source of at times highly technical minutiae. \u0022I spent as much time on that issue as I have spent on any issue, probably, in fifteen years in politics,\u0022 Gibbs says. \u0022For probably two months, it was virtually everything I did. We were joking the other day, after the well got sealed, and somebody said, \u0027Gibbs, what are you going to do with all that stuff you know about oil?\u0027 And the president said, \u0027You should go be a consultant [for an oil company] right now.\u0027\u0022\u000A\u000ABut on May 21, the leak was still gushing, and several reporters pummeled the press secretary with questions about the federal government\u0027s seeming helplessness on the matter. Gibbs grew infuriated by the insinuations, particularly by CBS\u0027s Chip Reid, that the administration was not doing all that it could do to improve BP\u0027s floundering response. After the briefing, he met individually with several reporters in his office and heatedly dressed them down. To one of them he asked, \u0022What\u0027s the point of me spending two hours every morning getting briefed on all of this if you\u0027re just going to be asking me the same questions over and over?\u0022\u000A\u000AGibbs had a point, but not as much of one as he believed. Some of that day\u0027s questions—\u0022Is the president satisfied with BP?\u0022 \u0022If they\u0027re not getting the job done, does the government just stand there as a spectator and hope for the best?\u0022—did come off as inane. On the other hand, says one of the correspondents present, \u0022It was necessary to press them on the who\u0027s-in-charge point, because while they\u0027d been giving replies, they were neither making sense nor squaring with the facts at the time, so they didn\u0027t count as answers. So too bad for them that they had to keep dealing with the same line of questioning.\u0022\u000A\u000A···\u000A\u000AOne day, perhaps as soon as the end of this year, Robert Gibbs will step back from the podium, away from the food fight that is his daily bread, and assume the more ethereal climes of big-picture strategist. On rare occasions, he has been given a glimpse of what it will be like to float above the mosh pit. This summer, he accompanied the president to a Chrysler factory in Detroit. Obama was there to extol the improved fortunes of the automaker as a result of the federal bailout.\u000A\u000A\u0022I was in the Roosevelt Room when the final decisions were made on the two auto companies,\u0022 Gibbs recalls. \u0022And I remember Chrysler was the one we discussed last. I\u0027d asked someone before the meeting to pull together stuff on where the Chrysler plants were. And I spoke up at the meeting toward the end and said, \u0027These communities where the plants are, they\u0027re already at 17 to 19 percent unemployment.\u0027 The policy folks had said, \u0027Even with the money, it\u0027s 51–49 whether Chrysler ever makes it.\u0027\u000A\u000A\u0022But at that Chrysler plant in Detroit, I remember standing next to Brian [Deese, the White House\u0027s auto-recovery czar] and listening to those workers cheer. And I looked at Brian and I said, \u0027You know what? It\u0027s nice, a year and a half after sitting in that room and arguing like you and I did that this made a lot of sense, to watch the people in Detroit at that plant who can raise their families with the hope of living the dream that their parents and their grandparents who worked in those same plants did.\u0027\u0022\u000A\u000AFrom behind his cluttered desk, Gibbs\u0027s small eyes seem to shimmer a bit. \u0022And so,\u0022 he says, \u0022as many days as you come in here and you roll that boulder up the hill, and maybe more often than not it rolls back on you—it\u0027s a day like that where you say, \u0027You know what? If you roll the boulder up the hill, it makes a difference.\u0027\u0022\u000A\u000AAlas, the headlines following the Chrysler-factory visit were not about the folks in Detroit whose jobs were saved. Instead, the media focused on the Commerce Department\u0027s discouraging economic report, the worsening conditions in Afghanistan, and Chelsea Clinton\u0027s wedding. So for Robert Gibbs and the White House, it was not a good news day. Just a good day.\u000A\u000ARobert Draper is a GQ correspondent.",
  	    "author": ["Robert Draper"],
  	    "keywords": ["News","Politics","Robert Gibbs","White House","Press Secretary","Barrack Obama","BP","Washington"]
